concept_explanation.arrays_fill:
**`Arrays.fill(array, value)`** — fills the array with a single value.

```java
int[] zeros = new int[5];
Arrays.fill(zeros, 0);  // [0, 0, 0, 0, 0] (redundant — already 0)

int[] ones = new int[5];
Arrays.fill(ones, 1);  // [1, 1, 1, 1, 1]

String[] placeholders = new String[3];
Arrays.fill(placeholders, "TODO");  // ["TODO", "TODO", "TODO"]
```

Useful for initializing arrays to non-default values. Common in game grids (fill with empty cells), data analysis (initialize counters), etc.

concept_explanation.passing_arrays_to_methods:
Arrays as method parameters work just like other types — but remember the reference semantics from last topic.

```java
public static int sumArray(int[] arr) {
    int total = 0;
    for (int n : arr) {
        total += n;
    }
    return total;
}

// Call:
int[] nums = {10, 20, 30};
int result = sumArray(nums);  // 60
```

**Returning arrays** from methods:

```java
public static int[] doubleAll(int[] arr) {
    int[] result = new int[arr.length];
    for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
        result[i] = arr[i] * 2;
    }
    return result;
}

// Call:
int[] original = {1, 2, 3};
int[] doubled = doubleAll(original);  // {2, 4, 6}
```

**Critical pattern decision: modify in-place OR return new array?**

**In-place** (modifies original):
```java
public static void doubleAllInPlace(int[] arr) {
    for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
        arr[i] *= 2;
    }
}
// Caller's array is changed.
```

**New array** (original unchanged):
```java
public static int[] doubleAll(int[] arr) {
    int[] result = new int[arr.length];
    for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
        result[i] = arr[i] * 2;
    }
    return result;
}
// Caller's array unchanged. New array returned.
```

**Which to use?**
- **In-place**: memory-efficient (no extra array), good for large data
- **New array**: safer (no surprise mutations), better for utility functions

In doubt: return a new array. Surprising mutations cause bugs. Production code generally prefers immutability when possible.

concept_explanation.linear_search_method:
Searching for a value in an unsorted array — there's no shortcut. You must check each element. This is **linear search**.

```java
public static int linearSearch(int[] arr, int target) {
    for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
        if (arr[i] == target) {
            return i;  // Found at index i
        }
    }
    return -1;  // Not found (sentinel value)
}

// Call:
int[] nums = {5, 12, 3, 8, 17};
int idx = linearSearch(nums, 8);  // 3
int notFound = linearSearch(nums, 99);  // -1
```

**Time complexity**: O(n). In the worst case (target at end or not present), you check every element.

**Standard convention**: return -1 when not found. ALL search functions in Java use this pattern.

**Why -1?** Because it's not a valid index — any valid index would be 0 or positive. The caller can check `if (idx == -1)` or `if (idx < 0)`.

concept_explanation.binary_search_intro:
If the array is SORTED, you can search much faster using **binary search**.

**Idea**: Check the middle element. If it matches, done. If target is smaller, search the LEFT half. If larger, search the RIGHT half. Repeat. Each step ELIMINATES HALF the array.

```java
public static int binarySearch(int[] arr, int target) {
    int left = 0;
    int right = arr.length - 1;

    while (left <= right) {
        int mid = (left + right) / 2;
        if (arr[mid] == target) {
            return mid;
        } else if (arr[mid] < target) {
            left = mid + 1;  // Search right half
        } else {
            right = mid - 1; // Search left half
        }
    }
    return -1;
}
```

**Time complexity**: O(log n). For 1 million elements, only ~20 checks max. For 1 BILLION, ~30 checks.

**REQUIREMENT**: array must be sorted. If not sorted, binary search produces garbage results.

**Java's built-in**: `Arrays.binarySearch(arr, target)` — same algorithm, returns same -1 for not found.

Binary search appears in interviews CONSTANTLY. Memorize this pattern.

concept_explanation.array_reversal:
Reversing an array — common interview problem. Two main approaches:

**Approach 1: New array (simple)**

```java
public static int[] reverse(int[] arr) {
    int[] result = new int[arr.length];
    for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
        result[i] = arr[arr.length - 1 - i];
    }
    return result;
}
```

Walk forward through result, backward through input.

**Approach 2: In-place (memory efficient)**

```java
public static void reverseInPlace(int[] arr) {
    int left = 0;
    int right = arr.length - 1;
    while (left < right) {
        // Swap arr[left] and arr[right]
        int temp = arr[left];
        arr[left] = arr[right];
        arr[right] = temp;

        left++;
        right--;
    }
}
```

Two pointers (`left` from start, `right` from end). Swap them. Move toward middle. Stop when they meet.

**This 'two-pointer' technique** is one of THE most important interview patterns. Used in: reverse, palindrome check, two-sum (sorted), remove duplicates. Master it.

**Swap pattern**: needs a `temp` variable. Java doesn't have tuple-unpacking like Python (`a, b = b, a`).

step_by_step_solution.details:
First, import Arrays. Then create the data:

```java
import java.util.Arrays;

public class Leaderboard {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] scores = {78, 92, 65, 88, 95, 71, 83, 90, 67, 85};

        // Work in main here
    }
}
```

10 student scores. We'll process them through several methods.

```java
public static void printScores(int[] scores) {
    System.out.println("Original scores: " + Arrays.toString(scores));
}
```

One-liner thanks to `Arrays.toString`. No manual loop needed for printing. This is THE most useful Arrays method.

Java's `Arrays.sort` sorts ASCENDING. For descending, we sort ascending then reverse. To avoid modifying the original, copy first:

```java
public static int[] getSortedDescending(int[] scores) {
    // Copy so we don't modify the original
    int[] sorted = Arrays.copyOf(scores, scores.length);

    // Sort ascending (in-place on the copy)
    Arrays.sort(sorted);

    // Reverse to make descending
    int left = 0;
    int right = sorted.length - 1;
    while (left < right) {
        int temp = sorted[left];
        sorted[left] = sorted[right];
        sorted[right] = temp;
        left++;
        right--;
    }

    return sorted;
}
```

Three steps: copy, sort ascending, reverse in-place on the copy. The original `scores` array is untouched.

**Why copy first?** If we just did `Arrays.sort(scores)`, the caller's array would be modified. Sometimes desired, often not. As a UTILITY method, returning a new array is safer.

After sorting descending, the highest score is at index 0 (rank 1), second highest at index 1 (rank 2), etc. Rank = index + 1.

Problem: built-in `Arrays.binarySearch` requires ASCENDING sort. Our array is descending. We have two options:

Option A: Use linear search on descending array (simpler)
Option B: Use binary search but on the ascending copy (cleaner, faster)

For pedagogical value, let's write our own binary search that handles descending order:

```java
public static int findRank(int[] sortedDescending, int targetScore) {
    int left = 0;
    int right = sortedDescending.length - 1;

    while (left <= right) {
        int mid = (left + right) / 2;
        if (sortedDescending[mid] == targetScore) {
            return mid + 1;  // 1-based rank
        } else if (sortedDescending[mid] > targetScore) {
            // Target is smaller, look RIGHT in descending array
            left = mid + 1;
        } else {
            // Target is larger, look LEFT
            right = mid - 1;
        }
    }
    return -1;  // not found
}
```

For descending arrays, the comparison logic FLIPS. If middle > target, target is later (right). If middle < target, target is earlier (left).

**Note**: this binary search assumes no duplicate scores. If duplicates exist, returns position of any matching element.

```java
public static int[] getTopN(int[] sortedDescending, int n) {
    if (n > sortedDescending.length) {
        n = sortedDescending.length;  // cap at array length
    }
    return Arrays.copyOf(sortedDescending, n);
}
```

Defensive check: if requested top 100 but only 10 scores, return all 10 (don't crash). Then `Arrays.copyOf` does the slicing.

One line of real work. Java's library does the heavy lifting.

```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
    int[] scores = {78, 92, 65, 88, 95, 71, 83, 90, 67, 85};

    printScores(scores);

    int[] ranked = getSortedDescending(scores);
    System.out.println("Ranked (high to low): " + Arrays.toString(ranked));

    int[] top3 = getTopN(ranked, 3);
    System.out.println("Top 3: " + Arrays.toString(top3));

    int targetScore = 88;
    int rank = findRank(ranked, targetScore);
    System.out.println("Score " + targetScore + " rank: " + rank);

    // Verify original wasn't modified
    System.out.println("Original unchanged: " + Arrays.toString(scores));
}
```

Every line uses a method we built. main() reads like a high-level description — exactly the engineering style from Module 2.

